text:
China, officially known as the People's Republic of China (PRC), is the world's most populous country and the second-largest by land area. Located in East Asia, China has a rich history that dates back thousands of years, with notable dynasties such as the Qin, Tang, and Ming shaping its culture, politics, and economy. In 1949, the Communist Party of China, led by Mao Zedong, established the current government after a prolonged civil war. Since then, China has evolved from a primarily agrarian society to a global economic powerhouse, especially since the late 20th century, when market reforms were introduced under Deng Xiaoping.

China is known for its vast and diverse landscape, ranging from deserts like the Gobi to fertile plains along the Yangtze and Yellow rivers, as well as towering mountain ranges such as the Himalayas. The country boasts a rich cultural heritage, including major contributions to philosophy, literature, art, and technology, with Confucianism and Buddhism having a profound influence on its society. Mandarin Chinese is the official language, and the majority of the population is Han Chinese, though there are numerous ethnic minorities.

China has a one-party system, with the Communist Party maintaining strict control over political and civil life. Its growing influence on the global stage is marked by significant trade relationships, advanced technological development, and its Belt and Road Initiative, aimed at enhancing infrastructure and economic connections across Asia, Africa, and Europe.

Despite its economic success, China faces challenges, including human rights concerns, censorship, and regional tensions such as those over Taiwan and in the South China Sea. Nonetheless, it remains one of the most important countries globally, shaping the future of international politics, economics, and culture. Edit: I took like two hours to write this. text: Chongqing is located on the southeastern edge of the Sichuan Basin, surrounded by high mountains, and the ground is also rugged, the wind speed is very small, the wind is weak, and the frequency of static wind is quite large. During the day, the ground temperature is quite high, and the evaporation process is constantly intensifying, so that the air contains a lot of water vapor; Nights, especially clear and breezy nights in autumn and winter, are quite long and the radiative cooling of the ground is noticeable. At the same time, the cold air from the mountains at the edge of the basin sinks down the slopes, causing the air near the surface to cool down dramatically, eventually reducing the ability of the air to hold water vapour, and the excess water vapour condenses to form fog.

text: Ive been living in Chongqing for over 5 years now. My favorite things about the city is, that its literally built to integrate the mountains. It takes only a few minutes ride on one of the cheap rented electronic motorbikes to get to a hiking trail within the mountains. Secondly, the fog. Chongqing is mostly covered by a blanket of fog, due to its special geographical location. This makes sunrises, sunsets and walks through bamboo forests quite mystical. Then, living in such a vertical city has the advantage, that despite the size of the city, you rarely need to take a car or long transit for anything. As long as you live close to where you work or study, anything you could ever want is in walking (plus elevator) distance, or can be brought to your doorstep within 20 minutes. Lastly, regarding prices, while some renting can be quite affordable, especially if you¬¥re single without kids and will live there more short term, its easy to get a 200-300 $/month appartement, but if you want more comfort and less problems for your long term stay, you should expect prices closer to western prices (1000-2000$/month). Food can be cheap, interestingly buying at big supermarket chains and cooking yourself is more expensive than eating in nice restaurant, but food bought from smaller markets or street stalls has better quality and prices. For foreigners moving in here i recommend to wear masks in overcrowded areas and subways and always use hand disinfectant before touching your face, as there are many small viruses going around, which locals have build a strong immunity to. I used to catch a cold every month for the first two years i lived here. While like with most Chinese cities, successful integration is not easy, and will require a lot of bravery and initiative on your part, but compared to other cities, Chongqingnese are very open and warmhearted, and quickly form friendships.

text: I was an American that once lived in Chongqing for nearly 8 years. It is an absolutely incredible city even though it is barely known to the outside world. The main square with the clock tower near the intercontinental is iconic and has developed so much, the monorail system is cool, there was bomb shelters scattered across the hillsides of the downtown area, and so much more. Being a foreigner in a place with so little foreigners (though currently a larger Korean population) it is so nostalgic to look back and think of all the unique places us foreigners got to share together, from YCISCQ international school, the Tex-Mex in one of the malls, Dr. Dennis at the Global Doctor, Palm Springs, Blue Lake, the IKEA & Go Go Jump next door, Metro, it is just so nostalgic. Thank you God for blessing me with such an incredible experience and time in Chongqing and I can't wait to visit.

text: The difference is the "Seoul metropolitan area" has dozens of political election districts and therefore many mayors and different city/town rules and ordinance. Chongqing has only One mayor and the same city rules and ordinance for the entire municipality proper, and there are 32 million people under this mayor. and within its administrative proper.
author: @junxu3110

text: ‚Äã¬†@junxu3110¬† I know, but this is not about semantics. That's why I said it's a peculiar province designated as a city. If you're 80 km outside of Chongqing and you're in the mountains and you don't even see people or villages around, you don't say you're in the city, do you?
author: @threesixnine369six

text: ¬†@threesixnine369six¬† Chongqing is unique as the city is built among several mountain ridges. Therefore, they have 30+ city centers spreading out in the mountain valleys. Actually, you will run into many of these centers even 100 km away from the central district of Chongqing, for instance Fuling District, Wanxian District, and more.
author: @junxu3110

text: ¬†@junxu3110¬† You don't seem to get it. It's about density, not semantics. Just because Wanxian district is part of the "City of Chongqing" it doesn't change the fact that it's a district of towns and villages in the middle of nowhere, far far far away from the actual city of Chongqing. I know what a multicore city is, I lived in London and Seoul and visited Beijing and Tokyo many times. Even smaller cities, like Berlin, can have multiple cores. But to travel between these cores, you usually travel in an urban area, not coming from 200km away through mountains and valleys and forests. That's why I said Chongqing is a peculiar province designated as a city. Look at Tokyo for example, it's a peculiar prefecture of about 13 million people, but if you're in Okutama in the mountains, or on some of the small tropical islands that are part of the prefecture of Tokyo, you don't say you're in the city. When people refer to Tokyo as the most populous city in the world with anything between 34, 38 and even 40 million people, they knowingly or unknowingly refer to the highly urbanised agglomeration that is the Tokyo metropolitan area or sometimes the whole Kanto plain, but that is valid, because it really is an almost continuously built up area. To travel from the central part of Congqing to Qianjiang District, you're literally traveling through the countryside, and through mountains. That's not what cities are. So the whole province might be weirdly designated as a city, but the city is only the urban built up metropolitan area of Chongqing, which is big, but it's neither 32 nor 36 million people big like so many people claim.
author: @threesixnine369six

text: ¬†@threesixnine369six¬† I know exactly what you mean and you're confused city's population with density. By density, neither Chongqing nor Tokyo is the largest city in the world. By density, neither India nor China is the largest country in the world. It's not about density,; it's about the number of people living within a Juristically Delineated Administrative area by a country's Legislative system. The term "urban area" does not have a clear definition, is vague and not subjective enough.
author: @junxu3110

text: ¬†@threesixnine369six¬† In fact, Chongqing has changed the concept that a city must be a continuously built up area. That concept only applies to cities built on a flat topography including London,  Tokyo, New York, Paris, Shanghai, Beijing, to name a few, but Chongqing isn't.
author: @junxu3110

text:
¬†@junxu3110¬† I didn't confuse density with population, I didn't talk about densely populated countries and I didn't talk about densely populated cities, I only mentioned density in the context of "there's almost no density for 200 km between Chongqing and Wanxian". It's about the built up density and the distances between built up areas. 

Just because it's legally called a city it doesn't make it a city. It's a historical and political quirk.

Let's go for a hypothetical situation. 
We're two decades into the future and the new president of China wants to rearrange some borders and change some names. 
Sichuan is to absorb Chongqing and be renamed into "The City of Chengdu". Does that mean the Tibetan towns and villages up in the mountains, and the central district of Chongqing are now part of the city of Chengdu? No, they're part of the province called "The City of Chengdu" but they're not actually part of the actual proper city of Chengdu or its metropolitan area.
Hebei and Tianjin are to be made part of Beijing. Is Cangzhou really a part of Beijing? 
Does that all sound a bit ridiculous? Yes. That's the point.

As for city typologies, there are other big cities and metropolitan areas where mountains divide some parts of the city, like in Hong Kong or Seoul, or Rio de Janeiro, but these mountainous areas are not hundreds of kilometres long. So Chongqing didn't really change any concept of continuous built up areas.
The province of Chongqing is bigger than many countries.
The actual metropolitan area of the city of Chongqing is no larger than Moscow.
author: @threesixnine369six

text:
¬†@threesixnine369six¬† Chongqing was established as a municipality city by the Chinese legislation. It's not different than the other three municipality cities in China, or you will likely call them the province of Shanghai, the province of Beijing, and the province of Tianjin. 

By singling out  the "urban population" of Chongqing using some arbitrary measures such as distance and density, and comparing that with those of the Kanto Plain, we are not comparing the same thing within an administrative proper. How short the distance must be between two city centers in oder to make them as a city together? How dense is dense enough for being called as city? Chongqing does change the traditional concept used for cities built on flat topographies.

Oh yes, if someday the entire Sichuan plus Chongqing were combined as the city of Chengdu by the legislature in China, than be it and that is exactly  what it should be called.

Have you ever been to Chongqing? To say the city is no larger than Moscow makes me believe you know about Chongqing only from inaccurate internet sources.

text:
I want to analyze it. Western media have described it as the Chinese government blocking the products of YouTube, Facebook or Google, but this is not the case. The fact is that these service providers have voluntarily withdrawn from China.
In 2014, a terrorist attack occurred in Xinjiang. The terrorists spread rumors and encouraged violence through Facebook groups. The Chinese government hopes that Facebook officials can clean up these violent content and rumors, and require Facebook to set up data servers in China, which is similar to the Biden administration's request a few years ago that Tiktok set up its servers in the United States and accept supervision. The final difference is that Tiktok accepted the request of the US government and set up its data servers in the United States; but Facebook did not accept the request of the Chinese government and voluntarily withdrew from China. The service providers who did the same also include Google.

The final result was described by Western media as the Chinese government blocking YouTube and Facebook. I can only say that this is very American

text: I'm an American who used to live in China. Chongqing was easily one of, if not my favorite cities in China and possibly the world too. And somehow despite all of that almost none of my friends have any clue what Chongqing is, they didn't even know it existed. text:
Great video! I've been to Chongqing and it is one of my favorite cities in the world. It actually has closer to 20m people than 30m in the urban area. The 30m figure includes surrounding rural areas in the entire direct-administered municipality (around the same size as Austria).
Chongqing "municipality" was carved out of Sichuan Province in 1997, including the rural countryside. Tokyo is still the world's largest "urban area" -- which is a better way to think about urban populations than "city" political boundaries, which can divide urban areas into separate cities or in this case, expand cities beyond urban areas.

text:
Big Drew Binsky fan here, I partially grew up in Chongqing, although it‚Äôs absolutely a dope place that I would highly recommend everyone to visit, the claim that it has 30 something million people or it is the biggest city in the world is a total myth. 

Similar to New York City vs New York State which many outside of the US often get confused with, Chongqing is actually both a city and a prefecture(like a province) with the same name, the prefecture has a land size similar to South Korea and within its jurisdiction it has a population of 36 million, but not the city itself, that number includes people living in townships and smaller cities within the same prefecture that can be 10 hours away by car crossing mountains, forests, farmlands and rivers. I think the actual Chongqing city has roughly a 15 million population size, still massive of course, but much more realistic. 

Hope someone finds this info helpful. Stilling lovin your good work Drew, welcome to my city, keep up the good work.

text: ¬†@DDDrumpf¬†  It's unclear if you're trying to be sincere or play a game.  No, I'm not trying to give an "English lesson".  I'm only saying that there's a confusion when there are two things with the same name (as we see on the map, the large region is labeled as Chongqing, and there is a dot inside it which is also labeled as Chongqing).  Without giving any reason, the Chinese call the larger thing a "city" and don't tell us what the smaller thing is.  In the English-speaking world, the thing designated on the map with a dot is called a city.  The larger region is perhaps better termed a "prefecture" or "administrative region" in ordinary English.  But someone decided to use a translation that's inconsistent with how the word "city" is used in the English-speaking world, and this mislabeling is now entrenched, unfortunately.  That is the cause of the confusion (as already noted by hiweirdbot and many others).

text: I live in the US. Where I live (a well-known big city), mostly chain restaurants are scattered along long stretches of streets, with little to marvel at. Many concrete buildings, and no community. People don't really walk here. You either get in a car, or some other means, from A to B and back. To get a fraction of the feeling of what I'm gathering from Chongqing, your best bet is a multi-level shopping plaza (if it still exists and hasn't become a ghost mall.) There is a reason people feel so alone and disconnected here. Because we are. Everything is so stretched out, so far away and few options of places we can gather together the way we see in the city Chongqing. The income inequality keeps people trapped from car to job, job to home with little opportunity to walk among fellow citizens to enjoy some street food. Hurts that when people think of the US, their first thought is gun violence. We need to do better.

text: I must clarify that the fog in Chongqing is not air pollution. It is mainly because Chongqing is located in a mountainous area with a well-developed water system. The evaporated water vapor is not easy to dissipate and shrouds the city all year round. This forms a fog that cannot be dispersed for a long time. This is why locals like to eat spicy food, because it can remove dampness (from the perspective of traditional Chinese medicine)

text:
¬†@wkrp01¬† I think you're mistaking what I'm saying. I'm not disagreeing with your assessment of Chongqing as a "city." But for U.S. analogies, I'm arguing it's not a matter of how urban a given territory is; it's a matter of administration.

When it was founded, D.C. had 2 different municipalities; the rest was forest. But both of those munis were subject directly to the U.S. government. Now it's entirely urban, and governed as one "city," but it still has the same status. It's often considered a state equivalent for stats purposes (even though it very much isn't).

NYC is part of New York state, and therefore subject to that state's laws. There are many cities in China that are part of provinces, but Chongqing isn't.

‚Äã¬†@JonDTours¬† Tokyo by those accounts is still not king.  Actual Tokyo residents only number at around 9.3mil(as of 2020).  What people refer to as Tokyo with roughly 42mil or 36mil population, is the combined Greater Tokyo Metropolitan Area, which encompasses the 2nd most populous city in Japan, Yokohama, as well as the rest of Kanagawa prefecture, most of Saitama prefecture, the bulk of the populated part of Chiba prefecture, and parts of Tochigi prefecture(the Tsukuba area) as well.  It's also confusing because GTMA could be referred to in various names.  the 42mil number is the combined population of the entire Kanto region.  If we're talking about Tokyo Major Metropolitan Area (Êù±‰∫¨Â§ßÈÉΩÂ∏ÇÂúè) which is what i described above, then it's actually only 38mil at max limits, roughly similar to Chongqing Metropolitan Area, as per what MaxHeadroom said.  Chongqing's urban area ("city limits") is roughly 22mil, significantly more populous than Tokyo.  Shenzhen's urban pop of 17.6mil is roughly equivalent to Tokyo prefecture.

If using the Kanto number, then Greater Bay Area with it's 86mil pop, is the world's #1 population center.  (combined areas of the Pearl Delta region between Guangzhou and Hong Kong).

text: ¬†@leima2741¬† What I said was "ask anyone in China who knows how the word 'city' is used in English".  You still haven't done that.  "Shi" translates as "city" only in Chinese English, not in English English (i.e., standard English usage).  The correct translation into English English would be "administrative region" (or possibly "prefecture"), but since the mistranslation has been widely propagated, the confusion persists.  In order to avoid confusing people from countries that create their own non-standard meanings of English words, UN documentation uses the terminology "urban area" to mean what "city" ordinarily means in English English (unlike Chinese English, in which a "city" can include vast amounts of rural area).  The UN provides an explanation of this, titled "Definitions of cities and urban areas".
author: @wkrp01

text: ¬†@wkrp01¬† it is you who are confused with the definition of city. From the administration perspective, a city can be supervising several neighboring counties(Âéø), but when it comes to daily reference, a city means a city itself. They do not include a vast amount of rural areas. The idea of "Greater xxx" is used everywhere in the world, including Boston, NYC, Shanghai and even Tokyo.
author: @leima2741

text: ¬†@leima2741¬† Where you're off is that a "Shi" doesn't have "neighboring counties", because they consider a "Shi" to have the counties inside, not neighboring.  Also, in the West, "Greater" is used to indicate the sum of a "city proper" plus the suburbs that are outside but neighboring or near the "city proper".  A "Shi" doesn't have suburbs (meaning outside the line of the "Shi"), because the only things neighboring a "Shi" (i.e., outside the line) is other provinces.  When considering my previous explanation of English English vs. Chinese English, then everything becomes clear.
